    {
        "user": "UCUSW7WVD",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1645838782.428059",
        "client_msg_id": "700250d8-80cd-4d1f-a9df-4a4945a0ead6",
        "text": "I really agree with most of the article -- except this bit:\n&gt; Ultimately, they expect people to type code into a development environment. That has always seemed like a lack of vision, to me.\n&gt; \nImagine if you told someone having difficulty learning to write that others are lacking vision for expecting them to type letters into a keyboard. It feels confusing to tell them to wait for a technology that doesn't exist yet. I'd say it does them a disservice.\n\nI agree instead with your previous paragraph, that I quoted in my previous comment. We can only teach people what we know, though we can try to stage the concepts to be easier to learn. Anything else is research, something we have to learn ourselves before we can teach others.\n\nIt feels a little dissonant that the two diametrically opposed views are so close together. Did you intend them as separate ideas, covering the space of possibilities?",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
